    ## Topbar

    The topbar element is a navigation staple in UI patterns. Here we will handle things like application title, main top level navigation, global search, and some badge like indicators for places to take action.

  = partial "modules/topbar"

  .push-top
  :markdown
    #### Usage

    ~~~haml
    .topbar
      .title Wardrobe
      %nav
        %ul
          %li= link_to "Menu Item One", "#"
          %li= link_to "Menu Item Two", "#"
          %li
            = link_to "#", class: "icon-after caret-down" do
              More Menu
              %span.badge 42
            %ul.submenu
              %li= link_to "dropdown item 1", "#"
              %li= link_to "dropdown item 2", "#"
              %li
                = link_to "dropdown item 3", "#", class: "icon-after right"
                %ul
                  %li= link_to "flyout 1", "#"
                  %li= link_to "flyout 2", "#"
                  %li= link_to "flyout 3", "#"
              %li
                = link_to "#" do
                  dropdown item 4
                  %span.badge 42
          %li.search
            %input(type="text" placeholder="search")
    ~~~
  .push-top
  :markdown
    The badges in the `.topbar` are `$primary-color` by default when using the `.badge` class by itself. If you add any other semantic class like `[.error, .warning, .success]` it will change the color to match those color variables. Example: <span class="badge">12</span><span class="badge error">4</span><span class="badge warning">23</span><span class="badge success">19</span>

    ### Sub-topbar

    Beneath the main top bar is a sub topbar for additional "global" UI utilities and top-level data filtering like a date range or breadcrumb navigation on the left side of the bar. On the right side, there will be buttons like favoriting/unfavoriting views, generating artifacts for reporting and data export.

